Introduction

Trans-Gulf migrants (TGMs) travel long distances to forage and breed. These birds migrate from Central and South America every spring to more temperate regions between Texas and Florida. Their time of arrival to the breeding grounds have differing tradeoffs and can affect the fitness of the migrants. Early arrivals correlate with higher chances of mating and breeding while later arrivals benefit from surplus food availablility (Smith and Moore (2005)). One study that studied migration patterns from 1828-2010, found a uniform trend of earlier arrivals correlated with higher temperatures from 1978 to 2010 (Kolov et al. (2017)). In the face of climate change, populations of TGMs may decline if there is a failure to shift arrival dates in response to warmer temperatures (Both et al. (2006)). With an increase in species conservation among the public in the recent decades, many online programs are available for researchers to access and study. The Cornell Laboratory of Ornithology and the National Audubon Society have established the program eBird, a compilation of over a hundred million bird observations from thousands of contributors.

Methods

In order to study the effect of local weather conditions on the arrival time of TGMs in Massachusetts, the meteorological data from Mobile AL, Charlotte NC, and Boston MA were acquired from NOAAs National Climatic Data Centers API to examine five species of birds (Hylocichla mustelina, Archilochus colubris, Seiurus aurocapilla, Progne subis, and Icterus galbula) from eBird.

The arrival time for each species was considered to be the julian day when 25% of birds had arrived in a given year according to a logistic model. The birds were estimated to be in Mobile and Charlotte 10 and 5 days before the arrival in Boston, respectively. Using this, a rolling mean of temperature and wind data was taken over a two week period surrounding the dates that the birds were estimated to be passing through each location.

ANOVA analysis on maximum temperature, minimum temperature, and wind was performed to determine the effect these variables have on arrival date.

Figure 1: Map of the weather stations used along the migration route

Weather data from three stations, Mobile AL, Charlotte NC, and Boston MA were used to estimate weather conditions along the migration route to Massachusetts. Weather parameters assessed include maximum temperature, minimum temperature, and the wind vector.

Figure 2: logistic models representing the proportion of birds of each species arriving in Massachusetts each year.

The proportion of birds arriving in Massachusetts in a given year was modelled using a logistic curve.

##Discussion

Global warming has become a steady issue in the news, especially with conservationists. The trans-Gulf migrants are a specific group that have been at the center of studies because of their long distances traveled to forage and breed. Weather data was collected from Mobile, AL; Charlotte, NC; and Boston, MA to determine the weather conditions. It was found that the maximum temperature and the minimum temperature both increased. When the proportion of birds arriving early in Massachusetts was studied on a logistic curve, it was determined that more birds were arriving earlier than in previous years.

Both, Christiaan, Sandra Bouwhuis, CM Lessells, and Marcel E Visser. 2006. Climate Change and Population Declines in a Long-Distance Migratory Bird. Nature 441 (7089): 8183.
Kolov, Eva, Michael Matiu, Annette Menzel, Ji Nekov, Petr Lumpe, and Peter Adamk. 2017. Changes in Spring Arrival Dates and Temperature Sensitivity of Migratory Birds over Two Centuries. International Journal of Biometeorology 61 (7): 127989.
Smith, Robert J, and Frank R Moore. 2005. Arrival Timing and Seasonal Reproductive Performance in a Long-Distance Migratory Landbird. Behavioral Ecology and Sociobiology 57 (3): 23139.
